# Example /etc/cron.d/private entry for a claude-watch CONTAINER deployment.
#
# This file is the canonical example for "I want a recurring task to fire
# inside my claude-watch container". The container image (built from
# container/Dockerfile) ships its own cron daemon with /etc/cron.d/private
# reserved as an operator bind-mount slot. See container/compose.yml for
# the volume entry; see container/cron.d/cw-default for the baked-in
# defaults this file SUPPLEMENTS (it does not replace them — both fire).
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Installation
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# 1. Copy this file to a host path you want to bind-mount in. The
#    in-container path /etc/cron.d/private is a directory, so the host
#    counterpart is also a directory, and the file inside it can have
#    any name:
#
#        sudo mkdir -p /etc/claude-watch/private-cron.d
#        sudo cp examples/cron/private-example/private-example.crontab \
#                /etc/claude-watch/private-cron.d/index-refresh
#        sudo chown root:root /etc/claude-watch/private-cron.d/index-refresh
#        sudo chmod 644       /etc/claude-watch/private-cron.d/index-refresh
#
#    Files inside /etc/cron.d/ (including subdirectories) MUST be owned
#    by root and not be symlinks — cron refuses to load anything else
#    with "WRONG FILE OWNER" and skips it silently.
#
# 2. Uncomment the corresponding bind-mount line in container/compose.yml:
#
#        - "/etc/claude-watch/private-cron.d/:/etc/cron.d/private/:ro"
#
#    Adjust the host path to match step 1.
#
# 3. Recreate the container so it picks up the new volume:
#
#        docker compose up -d --force-recreate claude-watch
#
# 4. Verify cron sees the file (the supervisor log should show one line
#    per cron entry on reload):
#
#        docker compose exec claude-watch cat /var/log/cron.log
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Format
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Standard /etc/cron.d/ format: `m h dom mon dow user command`. The
# `user` column is REQUIRED for /etc/cron.d/ entries (unlike a
# `crontab -e` user-crontab, which omits it).
#
# Inside the cw container, the user MUST be `hndrewaall` — that's the
# uid-1000 account the image bakes for claude-watch, and the one
# /var/lib/claude-watch/ is owned by. Running as root inside the
# container bypasses every permission boundary the image sets up.
#
# claude-watch itself is on PATH at /usr/local/bin/claude-watch
# (image-baked). Spell out the absolute path in cron rows; cron's
# default PATH is the minimal /usr/bin:/bin, so anything not under
# those needs the full path OR an explicit PATH= line at the top of
# the file. Following the cw-default convention, this example uses
# absolute paths.
#
# stderr capture follows the same convention as
# container/cron.d/cw-default: redirect to /tmp/claude-watch-cron-*.log
# so operators can inspect failures via:
#
#     docker compose exec claude-watch cat /tmp/claude-watch-cron-index-refresh.log
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Customise
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Replace the INDEX_CMD placeholder with the actual command you want
# fired. The shape below — `claude-event "..." --tag <tag> --source cron
# --data <k=v>` — is the canonical "I refreshed something; here's the
# state" emission; consumers can route on the tag via
# tools/claude-event/routing.
#
# If your command is a script that lives on the host, bind-mount the
# script into the container too (e.g. via a second compose volume entry
# at /usr/local/bin/my-script), and have the cron row exec the
# in-container path.

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Pattern — periodic index refresh (every 6 hours)
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Reference shape: re-fire a long-running index/cache rebuild on a fixed
# cadence, then drop a claude-event so the attached session knows the
# refresh completed (or failed). 6h is a reasonable default for an
# index refresh — long enough that consecutive runs don't overlap, short
# enough that a cache going stale gets noticed the same day.
0 */6 * * * hndrewaall /usr/local/bin/claude-event "index refresh tick" --tag index-refresh --source cron --data cadence=6h > /tmp/claude-watch-cron-index-refresh.log 2>&1
